05122nam a22007815i 9780231555081DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315550817 a10.7312/katz203502doi  a(DE-B1597)627211  a(OCoLC)1350572299  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6431b.K3168 2022 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a363.325/11223/eng/202203151 aKatz, Rita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSaints and Soldiers :bInside Internet-Age Terrorism, From Syria to the Capitol Siege /cRita Katz. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Terrorism and Irregular Warfare00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tPROLOGUE: A DIFFERENT KIND OF BEAST -- t1 FROM JIHAD TO WHITE JIHAD -- t2 SCREW YOUR OPTICS -- t3 THE TERROR SYMBIOSIS -- t4 THE MAKING OF A TERRORIST -- t5 SAINTS AND SOLDIERS -- t6 CONTROL THE MEMES, CONTROL THE PLANET -- t7 THE VIRAL CALIPHATE -- t8 TERRORGRAM -- t9 SEX SELLS (TERROR) -- t10 TINFOIL HAT TERRORISM -- t11 FAR RIGHT 2.0 -- t12 WILL BE WILD -- tAFTERWORD: WHAT “CHANGE” LOOKS LIKE A YEAR LATER -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than a decade ago, counterterrorism expert Rita Katz began browsing white supremacist and neo-Nazi forums. The hateful rhetoric and constant threats of violence immediately reminded her of the jihadist militants she spent her days monitoring, but law enforcement and policy makers barely paid attention to the Far Right. Now, years of attacks committed by extremists radicalized online—including mass murders at a synagogue in Pittsburgh and mosques in Christchurch, New Zealand, as well as the Capitol siege—have brought home the danger. How has the internet shaped today’s threats, and what do the online origins of these movements reveal about how to stop them?In Saints and Soldiers, Katz reveals a new generation of terrorist movements that don’t just use the internet, but exist almost entirely on it. She provides a vivid view from the trenches, spanning edgy video game chat groups to mainstream social media platforms to what ISIS and Far-Right mass-shooters in El Paso, Orlando and elsewhere unwittingly reveal between the lines of their manifestos. Katz shows how the online cultures of these movements—far more than their ideologies and leaders—create today’s terrorists and shape how they commit “real world” violence. From ISIS to QAnon, Saints and Soldiers pinpoints the approaches needed for a new era in which arrests and military campaigns alone cannot stop these never-before-seen threats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOnline hate speech. 0aOnline social networks. 0aRadicalization. 0aRight-wing extremists. 0aTerrorism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/katz2035040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555081/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK